   "source": [
    "## Background and Prior Work\n",
    "\n",
    "The film industry is a global market where financial success is typically measured through box office revenue. However, not all films perform equally, and factors such as genre and production budget play a major role in determining success. Certain genres, such as action, adventure, and superhero films, are often associated with large production budgets and high revenue, while genres like drama or documentary tend to have smaller budgets and lower earnings.\n",
    "\n",
    "Previous research has shown that production budget is strongly related to box office revenue. Industry reports from Statista indicate that high-budget films generate the highest revenues. Other work using Kaggle movie datasets shows that action and adventure genres dominate revenue.\n",
    "\n",
    "Academic research also shows that blockbuster films benefit from economies of scale, meaning higher budgets can lead to higher returns. However, smaller films may still be profitable due to lower costs.\n",
    "\n",
    "Overall, both genre and budget strongly influence movie success, but their relationship is complex.\n"
   ]
  }
